images.description: Grigori "The Mad Monk" Rasputin. Buckle up, things are gonna get weird.

Picture it. Siberia. Middle of winter. 1869. Nothing good can come from this scene, right? Well, yeah kind of. Grigori Rasputin was born on 21 January 1869 in the tiny village of Pokrovskoye (which I can spell but not pronounce). If you are familiar with Russian geography, and all good Americans really should start making an effort at this point, this is in the modern Tyumen Oblast region. A happy little corner of the world where it rains or snows every day and everyone is a potato farmer.

We don’t know too much about Grigori’s early life aside from when he was born and who his parents were (Surprise! They were peasant farmers). Some sources describe him as an unruly child who fought, swore, drank, and stole his neighbors horses. I like to imagine him as the Bart Simpson of Pokrovskoye. Anyway Grigori goes to church and gets himself saved in 1897 and is a new man! That is until he catches a whiff of theosophy: basically a combo of Christianity and the occult.

So basically Grigori blacks out, sees a vision of the Virgin Mary, and wakes up having Jesus powers. Most impressive of all, he gets a reputation for being able to heal with his touch. He lives in a monastery for a while but decides to leave because of all the gay sex that is happening (no, seriously). He wanders the countryside eventually making it back home to Pokrovskoye and moves back into his parents’ basement.

WARNING: Lots of reading!!! 

 My mom ran away from my biological dad when I was 3. She married the man I call my Father. She tried to convince me that I never had a dad before she remarried but I was old enough to remember my biological father. 
  Every time I would ask about my biological father she would get defensive and say that he abused her physically/ mentally. I eventually stop asking and come to resent my Biological father. 
  Fast forward, I’m 19 years old. My biological father messages me on Facebook. He goes into vivid detail of memories he had with me in that short time span ( much of which I recall ) even being that young. Not going to lie, I cried. 
  From that time on my biological father and I communicated through Facebook for a year before I make the decision to fly down to Texas to meet him. He is remarried with 2 daughters aka my sisters. 
  We finally meet and it was simply amazing. He was a great man from what I could see but I was super standoffish towards him. He notices this and asks me why I’m being standoffish. I told him what my mother had told me growing up and he instantly went white in the face. He was in complete shock, completely taken back. It took him a minute to collect his thoughts. He could not believe it. 
  He goes through the entire story with me of his relationship with my mother. They were incredibly young (17-18) and they didn’t make very smart decisions. Turns out my mother was VERY manipulative. I already knew this because my mother had an affair with another Army guy while my dad was deployed and tried to manipulate my sister and I to believe that my deployed father was crazy.  He wasn’t crazy, not one bit. My mother spent every penny of his deployment money on top of maxing out all his credit cards. So it was easy to come to the conclusion that my mother would do anything to justify her actions. It was like history had repeated itself. 
  I’m happy I made the decision to meet my biological dad. I now have a relationship with a whole “new” family who never stopped believing that one day I would come back.

FP Edit:  Wow!  This community is amazing. I really appreciate all the positivity. I hope this helps others out there who are still unsure of what to do in situations like this.
P.S: Send nudes.

Some Elite Warriors of the Ancient World

images.description: In modern times we have many famous elite units such as the US Navy Seals or British SAS. The Ancient World also had its far share of elite warriors, although they were generally "Line Troops" rather than commando special forces.

The Egyptian War Chariots
(1500 BC-800BC)

The history of the War Chariot begins with Ancient Sumerian "War Wagon" a crude four wheeled cart essentially pulled by donkeys. This evolved into the sleek and dangerous war chariot pulled by fine horses. 

The mysterious Hyksos people introduced the War Chariot to the Ancient Egyptians, and these deadly weapons were used to expand Egypt's power. 

The War Chariot was a stable base for archery, and using its wicked speed a warrior could encircle and disrupt enemy formations.

Some notable chariot battles include the Battle of Meggido and the Battle of Kadesh.  Both sides in these conflicts used war chariots, and there would be thousands of chariots racing around the battlefield. 

Of course the average warrior would be an unarmored spearman. 

The Egyptians were some of the first people to accurately tally dead soldiers, they did this by cutting off and counting the right hands of the fallen enemy. In the Bible, the circumcised Israelites tally dead Philistines by collecting their foreskins!

Neo-Assyrian Siege Engineers
(900BC-600BC)

The Assyrians forged one of the greatest early empires, utilizing a professional army, iron weapons, and innovative new tactics. 

One of their greatest inventions was  the first recorded engineering corps. These engineers were tasked with breaking in to the well fortified cities of the ancient middle east.  To do this they invented all manner of siege techniques. 

These included siege towers, even floating siege towers when the town was surrounded by a river. They also invented a kind of battering ram (pictured above). This ram was well protected and included a built in tower for archers. The ram was used to chip away at the mudbrick walls that were used. The Assyrians also undermined city walls causing them to collapse.

The Assyrians were well known for their brutality and psychological warfare. This involved tactics such as as creating enormous piles of severed heads or impaling prisoners upon stakes.

I have a confession to make: I’m Nate Ruegger, a long-time Imgurian lurker, and an Animaniac. Some of my best childhood memories were voice acting as Skippy the Squirrel on my father's show Animaniacs. Now, about 25 years later, Animaniacs is coming back – but as many of you may not know, none of the original writers were asked back for this revival series. In fact, my father, who created Animaniacs, found out about the revival series by reading about it online like everyone else.

If you would like to see Hulu, Amblin, and Warner Bros. extend the courtesy of asking the original creator and writers to be involved in the next season of Animaniacs, please let them know by signing or sharing this petition: https://www.change.org/p/writeanimaniacsright

Animaniacs is very special to my father – the concept, the characters, and the storylines came from his life and our family. My father confided in me that if he gets shut out of the next seasons of Animaniacs, his heart may break into a thousand pieces. So I have to try. I have to at least ask one of you, some of you, for your help.

TL;DR - Animaniacs is coming back without any of the original writers and I, Skippy Squirrel, am asking you to please get the word out. Below is proof that I am in fact who I say I am.

Please forgive my potato-phone and help spread the word: https://www.change.org/p/writeanimaniacsright

Nico was a very old Gorilla who lived in Longleat Safari Park in the UK. He was jointly the oldest Gorilla on Earth with one other male. He was the oldest Gorilla in Europe at 56 years of age. The average life expectancy for a Gorilla is 35-40 years. For his 56th birthday last year his keepers made him a banana cake.

Nico lived on a purpose-built island with some keepers, but mostly by himself, away from the hustle and bustle of the other Gorillas. On tours, visitors to Longleat Safari Park would float past his island on tour boats and be told stories about him. Sometime's you'd see him chasing birds off of his island, arms flailing in the air, like a grumpy old man chasing kids off his lawn.
Here he is, eying up an intruder.

I Arted on my Son's Lunch Bags - 2017

images.description: I'm a dad in Southern California, and for about 4 years or so, I've been drawing on my son's brown paper lunch bags when he took them to school. They take about an hour each, sometimes a little more if I get ambitious. I try not to take too long, and it goes by quick when you're watching TV, or Netflix. I will use paints, markers, and colored pencils until I get the desired effect.

When my son was young, he was pretty shy. My wife and I would sign him up for extra-curricular classes or summer fun. Even though he loved taking new classes,  none of his friends from school would be there, and he was fairly introvered and standoffish when meeting new students.  We'd ask him how the day was, and he'd say he didn't know anyone and he ate lunch alone.

So I started doing these art pieces on his brown lunch bags to help break the ice, and get conversations going.  It worked! The more outgoing kids would come up to him and ask him about the artwork, and if the lunch art was some superhero, they'd have a conversation about the newest Marvel movie, or if it was an animal, they'd start talking about what animals were the coolest or roughest.

data.title: Flight couldn't take off due to a "weight imbalance"
data.description:
I was on a flight last year from Atlanta to New Bern, coming back from Jacksonville, FL for work.  I had a primo seat right in the middle and carefully planned as to not interfere with anyone's leg room.

I'm a big bearded dude, 5'9" and 280lbs.  I make sure to plan my flights very carefully, as I don't want to make anyone uncomfortable. T'was the perfect seat.

Flight attendant greeted us and the following conversation took place;

FA:  "Due to weight imbalance issue on the plane, we're going to have to ask if one person from rows 6 to 9 move to the rear of the plane.  The open seats near the restroom.  We'll even give you a free beverage."

[DEAD...SILENCE.]

FA:  "If we don't have any takers, we'll have to randomly select you to move."

[The air was thick--I realized that I was the isle seat in row 6.]

ME:  *raises hand* "I'LL DO IT....but I've got a question."

FA: "AWESOME! What is it?"

ME:  "Am I the weight imbalance?"

[The entire plane loses it, cheering and laughing.]

------------------------------------
After we got in the air, the flight attendent comes back to me:

FA: "What'll you have, sir?"

ME: "A bottle of water's fine, ma'am."

FA: "WATER?!"

ME "Y....yes?"

FA: *staring me down* "You SURE??"

ME "....a Coke, then?"

FA:  "You like Jack?"

ME:  "Yeah...?"

She walks off and returns with what could possibly be the strongest Jack-and-Coke I've ever had. 

No one on the flight was served drinks, just me.  The weight imbalance.  

5/7 would fly again.

Be good to each other!

/s/
LOTN

Meme explained: Ugandan Knuckles
data.description:
I've seen that Ugandan Knuckles meme is starting to be pretty popular in usersub and even on the front page lately. There's some confusion on it's origins and how it became a thing so fast so I'll try to clear things up a bit.

The meme originates from Uganda's first action movie "Who killed Captain Alex" by Wakaliwood studios. Most of the memes you see on the front pages are quotes from the movie. Phrases such as "Do you know the way?", "GWE GWE GWE", "Are you the queen" are all quotes from the movie in a mock African accent. If you're interested in the actual movie, it has English subtitles and can be found on Youtube for example. Few of the things like fake spitting and "clucking?" are just something that VRchat users created themselves.

Link to movie: http://youtube.com/watch?v=KEoGrbKAyKE

The Uganda memes have existed for quite some time before exploding all over the internet. Ugandan Knuckles is but a variation of the meme. Ugandan Knuckles is a popular character in a game called VRchat which is basically just a virtual reality game where you can create or choose your character and then interact with it with others. VRchat user "Gaztons" popularized the Ugandan Knuckles character which is from a parody video which was created as a 3D model and then used in VRchat. 

Gaztons, who is often referred as "the commander", went on a mission to recruit more players to join his tribe and it blew up all over the internet. A video uploaded by user "Stahlsby" currently has over over 4 million views on Youtube but you can find video compilations and highlights of Ugandan Knuckles tribe in VRchat and all over the internet.

Link to the Stahlsby's video: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Hxjofn2bYE8

The first ones to spread/create Uganda memes are considered to be Forsen's viewers. Forsen is a popular streamer on Twitch platform. Forsen and his viewers created memes and took the Uganda memes an extra mile further every chance they got and often linked and spread newly created memes among his community and even sent him Uganda's flag which can be seen on his stream's background sometimes. Even Forsen's donation and subscription sounds/emotes also relate to the Uganda memes. 

The Uganda memes especially took off when Forsen started to stream "Playerunknown Battlegrounds" which all of us are probably familiar with. Forsen's viewers would regularly "streamsnipe" which basically means getting in the same game as him and finding him in-game to shout quotes and memes from the Who killed Captain Alex movie. They even made a mock movie "Who sniped captain Forsen?".

Forsen's video. Warning: language/loud sounds. http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=07wHeiKeF6g

Forsen's community feel like the meme was stolen and ruined by the mainstream  (mostly by the VRchat's Ugandan Knuckles). Most of the ones using the quotes don't know where the meme originates from and only know a small fraction or only the "We know the way" (which actually refers to knowing how to use a gun in the movie) and it's being used way too much so that Forsen's community feel like it's being stomped to the ground at an incredible pace after being content for them for months. "We know the way" is but a fraction of the memes but the old memes are linked directly back to the Ugandan Knuckles so there is basically no point as the Uganda memes are being overused.

If you are interested for reason x or y, you can search for other popular quotes/memes of the Captain Alex movie.  It's somewhat hard trying to explain or paste the more popular quotes and memes (or at least they were more popular until "we know the way" took off) but you can find them from various highlights of Forsen videos for example. Memes on Forsen's videos often include other inside jokes but they're out there.

data.title: Shower thoughts are a real mind f*ck
We used to play video games for hours in a basement while eating a lot of fast food and telling bad jokes
data.description:
When I was 13 year old I met two people in high school, a guy and a girl, and we instantly got along and became a pretty good trio of friends throughout all of high school. Fast forward to 2 years later, we were all playing video games for hours upon hours at the girl's parents' house. We would play World of Warcraft in the basement while her mom would make us pizza upstairs and other cooked goodies. It was fucking great, some of the best years of my life. Well, for them it was literally fucking great, but at the time I had no idea. 

They would leave for like 2 hours in the middle of our gaming sessions and then return to play with me as if nothing had happened, and I was blasting music in my headphones and had no clue what they were doing in the meantime. The worst part is, they were super noisy and not trying to hide it at all, they thought I just knew and didn't care. Video games were pretty much all that I cared about at the time. But I had no idea, even though it lasted 3 years. Sadly when we were 18 they broke up and the guy moved away and we are not in touch anymore, but the girl is still one of my best friends. When she told me years later she couldn't believe that I didn't actually know this. I had one of those big "holy shit wtf how did I not know" moments and then we laughed about it for a while, but I still felt pretty ashamed that I was that oblivious.

This man has been my neighbour for nearly 2 years and the amount of respect I have for this man is unimaginable.

Meet Murry, this man  survived polio when he was 8, his right arm is unusable for all except his thumb.  He has successfully made a career of repairing vehicles till he retired 10 years ago.

Just this month he finished work on his very own hand built corby starlet airplane, it's taken him nearly 30 years to complete but I'll let him off for taking that long when you only have one useable arm. 

He lived with his brother Alan in the family house owned by his parents,until Alan had a stroke and passed away a few months ago.

 This man who has the maturity of a 7 year old but the knowledge of Gandalf! He's been there for me these past 2 years, giving advice when I've been down in the dumps, and giving just enough cheek to make you question if he really is a child trapped in his grandads body.
 
I leave for a new city and a new life in a months time but he has made such a huge impact in very little time, he means the world to me and I have no idea how I'm going to survive with out him being right next door.
 
Love you Murry, my honorary granddad
Wow thanks for all the comments, I'll try my hardest to upload some pics of his airplane when I finish work.

data.title: 11 years ago today, my entire world was changed forever.

images.description: I had just returned home after finishing my four-year enlistment with the Air Force that fall.  Over the months that followed, I told you about the girlfriend I had temporarily left behind in Alaska, and how you were going to be a grandpa.  You bought me and my new family a house, in my name, to help build my credit; and you even made the mortgage payments for me while I focused on finishing my degree.  I don’t think I told you how much I appreciated that.

You met your future daughter-in-law for the first time that fall.  I’ll never forget the wink and the “thumbs-up” you gave me when you first saw her.  You two seemed to really hit it off.  You even danced with her at my cousin's wedding.  She was starting to show too.  Only a few more months until you were going to be “Grandpa Dave”.

Winter break comes along, and you mentioned you were making a cross country trip to deliver a vehicle to San Francisco.  You asked if I wanted to come along and, having never been on a cross country trip before, I readily agreed.  I probably was too stubborn to admit it then, but I had also grown to miss you a lot those past four years, and I was happy to spend this time with my dad and best friend again.
